not having enough money or a lack of a white college education. Neither of the films addresses either of these issues, instead focusing on the problem of 'culture' and how that is the problem facing black Namibians and all Africans. It is a big problem, but I am not sure how it was supposed to be solved. Something about turning us black people completely to our 'traditional culture', some dumb thing. During one part he talks about singer Queen newzaincandownligh.cfbs.com/capsule-database/. None of this has anything to do with Namibian employees, colonial reception, Food Nation companies, and nothing I’ve ever heard about how Food Nation –food brands are used by military. That’s the big omission in these films, and one of the biggest factors in Namibian society.

And as to the University of Namibia – I don’t find it educational, informative and it has nothing to do with writing and persuasive my points. Interesting to read your comments. As a white Namibian I can understand your frustrations, especially as I have been hearing it all my life in respect of the Germans. Regarding the Power of Culture, the clip I saw was not specific in the issues it was trying to address but was targeting people in general «Don’t loose your local culture» «Don’t let Western culture take over» etc. Regarding your issues with German- Namibians being forced to speak afrikaans etc it is important to understand that
